HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1491
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of William Thomas "W.T."
Housley of Apison.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of William Thomas "W.T." Housley; and
WHEREAS, the son of Earnest and Lizzie Lee Roberts Housley, W.T. Housley was born
on January 9, 1935, in Decatur; his family later moved to Apison, where they operated a dairy
farm; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Housley served as a large equipment operator in the Apison and
Collegedale area for many years; and
WHEREAS, a man with many passions, W.T. Housley was an avid antique car
enthusiast; and
WHEREAS, he was also deeply devoted to his family and always endeavored to remain
true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Housley is survived by his grandson, Greg Housley; his son, James
(Sandi) Mansfield; his brother, L.D. Housley; and several nieces and nephews; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, he was preceded in death by his wife of sixty-six
years, Jean Bolden Housley; his only daughter, Cynthia Ann Housley; his brothers, Crawford
Housley, Hayden Housley, and Felix Housley; and his sisters, Margie Smith and Aileene Ball;
and
WHEREAS, throughout his many worthy endeavors, W.T. Housley distinguished himself
as a beacon of kindness, dedication, and loyalty; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should pay tribute to the bountiful life of this exceptional
Tennessean; now, therefore,
HJR1491
018219
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of William Thomas "W.T." Housley, reflecting fondly
upon his ability to live the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and condolences to the
family and friends of Mr. Housley.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
